name "sub:Concepts-and-terminology"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper has up to this point contrasted SWB with other accounts of or
 approaches to wellbeing and happiness.
 But SWB is not a monolithic concept; it is itself an umbrella term for
 a number of distinct ways of conceiving of a person's wellbeing.
 Many different survey questions have been taken as measuring SWB in the
 literature to date: the World Database of Happiness catalogues over a thousand
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "veenhoven:2007"

\end_inset

.
 These questions differ in a number of respects, including the breadth and
 timescale of experience encompassed, and the words in which the idea of
 wellbeing is expressed (which have included, for example: happiness; satisfacti
on with one's life situation, with life as a whole, or with quality of life;
 enjoyment of life; contentment; and many other variants).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Authors generally seem to have reflected rather little on the wide range
 of terms employed in research under the SWB banner, and to have shown a
 perhaps surprising lack of unease about this.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Even some who have noted the inconsistency of terminology in a context rather
 critical of SWB have have not flagged it as a potential issue 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "22"
before "e.g."
key "johns:2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Empirically, studies asking different questions have produced results that
 are generally fairly consistent with each other.
 But the use of different questions does make comparison of findings between
 studies problematic: it is difficult to be sure that any differences are
 not simply the result of nuances in the terms (and therefore concepts)
 in the questions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Communication and policy considerations may be one reason for the use of
 different terms, and the terminology used in reporting research may not
 match that used in the research itself.
 For example, a New Economics Foundation policy workshop identified 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

confusion/conflation with happiness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as a threat to the use of wellbeing in policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 24"
key "thompson:2008"

\end_inset

 even though in the report of this same workshop those terms are used interchang
eably and without clarification.
 On the other hand, 'happiness' seems to be used more widely than 'wellbeing'
 in media reporting of SWB research.
 Hence a study that actually asked respondents about 'life satisfaction'
 may be reported in the media as dealing with 'happiness' and to policy-makers
 as a 'wellbeing' study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
New bit
\end_layout

\end_inset

It seems possible, too, that economists have not wished to dwell on the
 variety of related but distinct wellbeing ideas because to do so would
 cast doubt on the potential for any one of them to represent a proxy for
 decision utility --- the thing that individuals seek to maximise --- and
 hence on the validity of their use for monetary valuation (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:happiness-valuation"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:happiness-to-economists"

\end_inset

, certain terms are used interchangeably in this paper too --- since essentially
 all the literature does so, it now appears impractical to do otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Domains and timescales
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:domains-and-timescales"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SWB can be measured using either single- or multiple-item scales.
 Multiple-item scales pose the question whether and how to aggregate the
 individual items.
 Some multiple-item scales focus purely on the evaluative aspects of SWB,
 asking about satisfaction in different life domains (work, relationships,
 finances, and so on --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
before "e.g."
key "cummins:2003"

\end_inset

).
 Others take a wider view, with items covering evaluative, hedonic and eudaimoni
c aspects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "huppert:2009"

\end_inset

.
 Still others, such as the General Health Questionnaire (GHQ), focus more
 on symptoms of unhappiness or psychological distress 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Clark:1994"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, research within economics has tended overwhelmingly to focus on
 single-item measures.
 On a pragmatic level, single-item measures have good data availability:
 they are included in several major surveys.
 Analysing a unitary quantity of something utility-like is familiar economic
 territory, and makes monetary valuation straightforward.
 And use of a single-item scale may be justified by the contention that
 the individual concerned is best placed to aggregate all the different
 aspects of his or her own wellbeing.
 On the other hand, single-item measures have poorer reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "huppert:2009"

\end_inset

 and, outside the discipline at least, not everyone is happy with an opaque
 and individualised aggregation function (for example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "michalos:2008"

\end_inset

 --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
after "360"
key "michalos:2008"

\end_inset

 --- writes that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moving Pandora’s Box of aggregation problems from the visible world to the
 invisible Black Box inside people’s heads does not strike me as a progressive
 research programme
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SWB can also be measured over various timescales.
 In the data most commonly used by economists, respondents are asked about
 the vague present (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

these days
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nowadays
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the last few weeks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and so on).
 These data are termed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

retrospective assessments
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kahneman:2006a"

\end_inset

, although in some cases future expectations could arguably be relevant
 too.
 In either case, there is a problematic lack of clarity as to what exactly
 is to be assessed on the time dimension.
 Even where the timescale of the assessment is more precise,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, some of the items devised by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "huppert:2009"

\end_inset

 ask specifically about the past week.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the recollection and aggregation of experiences has been shown to be systematic
ally distorted --- such as by neglect of experiences' duration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kahneman:2006b"

\end_inset

 --- relative to a simple average of momentary utilities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "robinson:2002"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, in respect of this benchmark, it could also be argued
 that a recollected and aggregated assessment is as valid a measure of SWB
 as a perfect integral of momentary experiences over time: humans do not
 live exclusively in the immediate present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Experience sampling or reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As implied by the above, SWB measures have been devised to approximate the
 average or integral of individuals' momentary utilities too 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 5"
key "kahneman:1999a"

\end_inset

.
 With a flavour of Edgeworth's 'hedonimeter', these come from either Experience
 Sampling Method (ESM) or Day Reconstruction Method (DRM) studies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In ESM studies, participants are signalled a number of times over a given
 period --- say, eight times a day, for seven days --- and are asked about
 aspects of their mental state, where they are, what they are doing, and
 who they are with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hektner:2007"

\end_inset

.
 In the medical literature, the term Ecological Momentary Assessment (EMA)
 describes a broad family of similar methodologies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "smyth:2003,shiffman:2008"

\end_inset

.
 The logistics of supplying and requiring participants to carry handheld
 computers or pre-printed response forms have until recently limited the
 scale of ESM studies, but technological developments are beginning to obviate
 this issue 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "collins:2003,goodwin:2008a"

\end_inset

, and one ESM study has already made use of respondents' own smartphones
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "killingsworth:2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DRM studies aim to collect similar information to ESM, but to do so less
 intrusively.
 These studies simply ask participants to break the previous day into episodes
 and to report the context of, and their feelings during, each episode.
 DRM data may be subject to greater recall bias than ESM data --- which
 is regarded as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gold standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 here --- but it also offers richer information on time use, given a fixed
 period of data collection, since it deals in periods rather than moments
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kahneman:2004a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, if it is judged most important to increase the wellbeing of those
 who have less of it (potentially for good philosophical and political reasons),
 this moment-in-time data is sometimes reduced to a measure of the proportion
 of time respondents report spending below some predefined threshold.
 This measure has been dubbed the U-Index 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kahneman:2006a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Interpretation and response
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regardless of the terminology used and the timescale asked about, what a
 respondent reports will depend on his or her own understanding of the question.
 Random variation between different individuals' interpretations --- as
 long as they are not wholly dissimilar --- may simply be regarded as a
 source of measurement error.
 The extent of this error may depend partly on the choice of terms, since
 some appear more capable of multiple interpretations than others (the word
 'happy' seems especially problematic, capable of expressing anything from
 momentary 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smiley-face feelings
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to self-realisation, flourishing and achievement --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "annas:2004"

\end_inset

).
 Multi-item scales, using a variety of terms, may help to reduce it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Culture and language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Non-random variation in interpretations represents a more serious challenge
 to the validity of SWB research.
 An obvious source of such variation is individuals' cultural and linguistic
 backgrounds.
 And there are identifiable cultural groupings in SWB ratings: historically
 communist countries may tend to lower scores; historically Protestant,
 island and south-American nations to higher ones 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "inglehart:2003,nef:2006"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given ratings' subjectivity, it is arguably impossible to determine how
 far cultural differences in ratings reflect varying levels of actual, experienc
ed SWB.
 However, different interpretation and reporting styles seem likely to be
 at least part of the story.
 While there may be some simple, universal concepts, 'happy', 'satisfied'
 and 'wellbeing' are probably not among them; for example, 'happy' appears
 weaker in meaning than straightforward translations in some other European
 languages --- including the French 'heureux', Italian 'felice' and Russian
 'sčastlivyj' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wierzbicka:2004"

\end_inset

.
 In some cultures it may also be important to distinguish public values
 from private values 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 3"
key "littlewood:2008"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "littlewood:2008"

\end_inset

's example concerns 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blood feuding clans in Northern Albania where the feud is regarded as a
 normal, even laudable and enjoyable, enterprise: families with a recently-kille
d member appeared to mourn only briefly and slightly...
 But on close questioning the women of the community, while subscribing
 to the public male ethos of the feud, would privately confide their distress
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 More generally, the potential for social desirability biases needs to be
 acknowledged and, ideally, minimised 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "tella:2005"

\end_inset

.
 For example, in some cultures it may be socially undesirable to be unhappy,
 or even to be too happy.
 In relation to East Asian cultures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "226"
key "uchida:2004"

\end_inset

 write that 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

emphasizing a success of the self may lead to jealousy and envy by others.
 The personal form of happiness is therefore often perceived to be tainted
 and incomplete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This all makes naïve comparisons of SWB between nations --- and perhaps
 even between different ethnic groups within nations --- problematic.
 Unfortunately, this has not stopped such comparisons being drawn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "inglehart:2003"

\end_inset

, for example, describe surprisingly large differences in SWB ratings between
 European countries in a paper that barely admits the possibility of cultural
 variability in interpretation and reporting.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These authors dismiss the possibility of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

translation problems
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the basis that the German-, Italian- and French-speaking Swiss report
 different levels of happiness than the Germans, Italians and French 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "167"
key "inglehart:2003"

\end_inset

.
 All this fact really demonstrates is that the differences in reported happiness
 between European nations are not 
\emph on
exclusively
\emph default
 due to language.
 Using similar data, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "layard:2003"

\end_inset

 notes that all three Swiss groups report similar levels of happiness to
 each other.
 But this does not rule out the possibility that differences in both their
 actual levels of happiness 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 their interpretations of the question serve to cancel each other out.
 And even if that were ruled out, extrapolating from this evidence to the
 much greater diversity of all the world's cultures seems weak, at best.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, there are ways around this issue.
 Studies limited to relatively local areas or relatively homogeneous cultural
 groups can produce interesting and valid data.
 Panel data can allow comparative analysis of SWB trends over time (at least
 if we can assume certain commonalities in the shapes of different countries'
 reporting functions).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However data from successive time periods could be unreliable over the long
 term if the meanings of words are not fixed.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "carlyle:1849"

\end_inset

 noted that economics was not a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gay science
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "530"
key "carlyle:1849"

\end_inset

; we would not now consider asking respondents how gay they feel.
 There is evidence of change in the meaning of 'wellbeing' too 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "2--3"
key "littlewood:2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Biological markers such as saliva cortisol levels or heart rate --- to
 be discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Is-happiness-valid"

\end_inset

 --- might help us to calibrate subjective responses cross-culturally 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "layard:2010"

\end_inset

.
 And the use of anchoring vignettes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "king:2003"

\end_inset

, which attempt to correct for differences in reporting functions between
 individuals, may prove informative, at least for the less subjective end
 of the spectrum of SWB questions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Response bias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability of obtaining any response to a SWB question may also vary
 from individual to individual.
 SWB questions generally receive very few missing responses relative to
 other survey items 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 654"
before "e.g."
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

, but the surveys of which they are a part tend, like all surveys, to attract
 response rates well short of 100%.
 Those who do not respond may be different in ways that are important for
 our understanding of SWB, at least at the population level.
 In the notation used above, the probability of even observing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 may depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, it is plausible that depressed people would be less likely
 to participate in social research, and that standard telephone and face-to-face
 survey methods might well attract respondents who are unrepresentatively
 lonely and/or trusting, both of which characteristics tend to correlate
 highly with SWB ratings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, if it is a social norm to be happy (unhappy), SWB responses ---
 at least in survey modes that are not self-completed --- might be biased
 upwards (downwards).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 371"
key "tella:2005"

\end_inset

 find little evidence that this occurs, however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dimensionality and boundedness
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:dimensionality-and-boundedness"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some writers have questioned whether SWB is reducible to a single dimension,
 and thus whether it is meaningful to ask --- as single-item SWB questions
 often do --- for a global evaluation of happiness, wellbeing, or satisfaction
 with life.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 46"
key "annas:2004"

\end_inset

 gives an example: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Suppose that you have just won the Nobel Prize; this surely merits the smiliest
 face.
 But suppose also that you have just lost your family in a car crash; this
 surely warrants the frowniest face.
 So, how happy are you? There is no coherent answer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 But although such an extreme example illustrates the problem clearly, real
 experience is rarely like this: affect is much more typically bipolar (happy
 -- sad) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "larsen:2001"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "684"
key "larsen:2001"

\end_inset

 explain: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

positive and negative affect are separable and...
 mixed feelings of happiness and sadness can co-occur...
 [M]any participants surveyed immediately after watching the film Life Is
 Beautiful, moving out of their dormitories, or graduating from college
 felt both happy and sad...
 [A]lthough affective experience may typically be bipolar, the underlying
 processes, and occasionally the resulting experience of emotion, are better
 characterized as bivariate.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the great majority of people have no difficulty in answering along
 one dimension 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 80"
key "praag:2004a"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
*** also -- you could alternatively use more indicators -- or use a method
 that might at least treat your one indicator more subtly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "boes:2004"

\end_inset

 ***
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
*** also reference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "huppert:2003"

\end_inset

 -- recommendations from reverse POV (should include +ve wellbeing in QoL
 -- whereas maybe econ should include some -ve wellbeing) ***
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boundedness of typical SWB scales has also been criticised.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 10"
key "wilkinson:2007"

\end_inset

, for instance, imagines: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there will be a point at which the entire population has finally climbed
 into the top happiness bracket.
 From that moment forward, average happiness must remain flat, simply as
 an artifact of the bounded scale, even if people continue to become happier
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Philosophically, such an argument presupposes that the 
\emph on
experience
\emph default
 of SWB is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 bounded, and that people cannot therefore know how happy it is possible
 to become --- an assumption that is at least open to doubt 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 18"
key "thompson:2008"

\end_inset

.
 This issue is also raised on a more practical level, in relation to analyses
 of longitudinal data where a bounded dependent SWB variable is regressed
 on potentially unbounded explanatory variables such as GDP.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 33"
key "johns:2007"

\end_inset

, like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "wilkinson:2007"

\end_inset

, argue that a genuine correlation between experienced SWB and GDP could
 go undetected in such analyses because of a ceiling effect, and suggest
 that this could be behind the SWB flat-line in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "easterlin:1974"

\end_inset

's seminal paper on the subject 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "easterlin:1974"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a number of counter-arguments to this: first, bounded variables
 can and do show time trends (fear of crime and social trust, for example,
 have varied over the recent past --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "dittmann:2005,putnam:1995"

\end_inset

); current data (in this case, ESS Round 3) place median SWB ratings at
 7 out of 10 and have fewer than 1 in 10 respondents answering in the top
 bracket, which suggests substantial room for upward movement; and analysis
 of time-trends against unbounded indicators is just one of many strands
 of SWB research.
 Finally, 
\emph on
unbounded
\emph default
 SWB scales are not impossible in principle --- for example, marketers sometimes
 use an 'unbounded write-in scale' where respondents make a number of marks
 of their choosing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stapleton:2005"

\end_inset

; alternatively, a scale could be developed using reference points that
 are not at the extremes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analysing happiness
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:analysing-happiness"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:ps-and-swb"

\end_inset

, the basic model underlying most SWB research relates an individual's reported
 happiness 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 to a vector of characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, via a happiness or utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and a reporting function 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R(h)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=H(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 The reporting and the underlying experience of happiness can rarely be
 disentangled, so 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are commonly collapsed into a single function mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The techniques used to estimate a particular model from the data depend
 on three factors.
 First, what questions are to be addressed? Economists are usually interested
 in determining whether and how much particular factors affect SWB --- commonly
 with a special focus on income measures and (un)employment, while controlling
 for other impacts.
 Second, what data sets are available? Are these at the micro (individual)
 level, or aggregated (for example, by country); do they comprise cross-sectiona
l, time-series, or panel data; what SWB items are included, what scales
 are the responses given on, and what other data is available for analysis?
 Third, and finally, what assumptions can reasonably be made regarding the
 SWB variables and the explanatory variables (both observed and unobserved)?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course these factors, and the statistical methods that follow from them,
 are in practice at least partially co-determined.
 In particular, one element of the development of the field has been the
 development or application of new statistical techniques in order to relax
 some of the more restrictive (and potentially unrealistic) assumptions
 required by earlier techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
SWB variable treatment and econometric models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:SWB-variable-treatment"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interpretation of SWB responses is one of the key subjects about which
 differing assumptions can be made.
 There are three main assumptions, of increasing restrictiveness, which
 are associated with a variety of different models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
A1.
 Reported SWB is a positive monotonic transformation of an unobservable
 underlying quantity of interest: 
\begin_inset Formula $R'>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
A2.
 Reported SWB is ordinally comparable between people: if 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}>r_{j}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}>h_{j}$
\end_inset

, where subscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 represent different individuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
A3.
 Reported SWB is cardinally comparable between people: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}-h_{j}=\omega(r_{i},r_{j})$
\end_inset

, where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is known up to a multiplicative constant; 
