\begin_layout Paragraph
Cardinal SWB comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the cardinality assumption, A3, simple OLS regressions are appropriate.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Alternatively, if respondents are thought to answer scale questions by the
 rounding up or down of a continuous latent quantity, interval regression
 would be suitable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "36"
key "praag:2004a"

\end_inset

.
 For example, a response of 9 would suggest an underlying value for interval
 regression of 8.5 -- 9.5; a response of 10 would suggest an underlying value
 of 9.5 or higher.
 Interval regression has not been widely used in the literature, however.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If a panel data set is available, the use of OLS makes it straightforward
 to include individual fixed effects (or use first differencing) to control
 for time-invariant unobserved influences on SWB 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
OLS models have been widely used in the psychology literature, but economists
 have tended to turn to them only when the use of aggregated (mean) SWB
 ratings has forced them to assume cardinality in any case (
\emph on
ibid.
\emph default
) --- see, for instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "welsch:2006"

\end_inset

 --- or when the OLS results have been shown to be qualitatively indistinguishab
le from the results of models not requiring cardinality --- as in the case
 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

, for example.
 In the latter case, OLS models may be preferred because of the straightforward
 interpretation of the coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subjectivity of SWB makes it difficult to assess the realism of the
 cardinality assumption.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "schwarz:1995"

\end_inset

 argues that respondents strive to make responses informative, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "praag:1991"

\end_inset

 argues that respondents may try to distribute reporting categories evenly
 with respect to the possible values of an underlying, unobservable quantity
 in order to maximise the information conveyed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

.
 Although these psychological arguments are undoubtedly highly speculative,
 results obtained using models that do and models that do not assume cardinality
 are usually extremely similar (
\emph on
ibid.
\emph default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Ordinal SWB comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relaxing the assumption of cardinality and turning to ordinal comparability,
 A2, many researchers have used the standard ordered probit and logit models.
 These models treat ordinal data (
\begin_inset Formula $r=1\ldots J$
\end_inset

) as the discrete expression of a continuous latent variable of arbitrary
 scale.
 On this basis they estimate two sets of parameters using maximum likelihood:
 first, a coefficient vector used to predict the latent variable from the
 explanatory variable vector (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

); and second, a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $J-1$
\end_inset

 cut-points, which are the values of the latent variable where there is
 a change in the observed discrete rating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In empirical economic research with ordinal data, including SWB research,
 these models 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fully dominate the literature
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 192"
key "winkelmann:2009"

\end_inset

.
 These models do not lend themselves easily to the inclusion of individual
 fixed effects for panel data (to control for heterogeneity in individual
 happiness and/or reporting functions), however; fixed effects specifications
 have therefore been rather little used in the economic literature to date
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Generalised ordered models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard ordered models assume (as OLS does) that the relative magnitudes
 of the effects of each of the explanatory variables are constant across
 the distribution of outcomes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 5"
key "boes:2006a"

\end_inset

.
 For example, the impact of income relative to the impact of marriage or
 divorce must be the same for those with low and high SWB levels alike.
 This is variously termed the proportional odds, parallel lines or parallel
 regression assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "boes:2006a"

\end_inset

 argue that single-scale SWB measures may be understood as measuring both
 unhappiness ('negative wellbeing') at the lower end and happiness ('positive
 wellbeing') at the higher end
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This recalls the discussion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:dimensionality-and-boundedness"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and that, since different factors may have different effects on these two
 dimensions, the parallel regression assumption might need to be relaxed.
 While the multinomial logit could be employed for this purpose, discarding
 information about the ordering of the response scale, this is inefficient.
 Instead, researchers have turned to generalised ordered response models
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "williams:2006,boes:2004,boes:2006,boes:2007,fu:1997"

\end_inset

, principally the generalised ordered logit and probit.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "boes:2004"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "boes:2004,boes:2006"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "winkelmann:2009"

\end_inset

 also describe a sequential ordered model and a finite mixture model; these
 are not discussed further here.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These generalised models effectively estimate a separate vector of coefficients
 for each cut-point of the latent variable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 126"
key "boes:2007"

\end_inset

; they give results that are similar to those of a series of binary logits
 or probits, taking each response level in turn and grouping responses on
 either side of it 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 59"
key "williams:2006"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For clarification, this grouping would proceed as follows.
 First, the lowest response (
\begin_inset Formula $r=1)$
\end_inset

 is contrasted with all higher ones (
\begin_inset Formula $r=2\ldots J)$
\end_inset

; next, the lowest two responses (
\begin_inset Formula $r=1,2)$
\end_inset

 are contrasted with all higher ones (
\begin_inset Formula $r=3\ldots J)$
\end_inset

; and so on.
 Finally, all responses but the highest (
\begin_inset Formula $r=1\ldots J-1)$
\end_inset

 are contrasted with the highest one (
\begin_inset Formula $r=J)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\emph on
partial
\emph default
 proportional odds model is also possible, and potentially the most useful
 variant: this is effectively a hybrid of the standard and generalised models,
 in which the parallel regression assumption is imposed on certain explanatory
 variables, which then take a single coefficient throughout the outcome
 distribution, but not on others (this can be automated by a stepwise process
 using likelihood-ratio tests).
 Applications of this model to BHPS and GSOEP data (with the inclusion,
 in some cases, of random effects) potentially vindicate concern over the
 parallel regression assumption; they suggest, amongst other things, that
 higher incomes may have a significant 
\emph on
negative
\emph default
 effect on the probability of answering in the very topmost SWB category
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mentzakis:2009,boes:2004,boes:2006a,winkelmann:2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Probit-adapted OLS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand Citet
after "p. 28"
key "praag:2004a"

\end_inset

 note that the standard ordered logit and probit models implicitly cardinalise
 SWB through the cardinal continuous latent variable underlying them, and
 on this basis suggest a method they term probit OLS or probit-adapted OLS.
 The probit-adapted OLS is a simple OLS model using a 'rough cardinalisation'
 of the ordinal SWB variable: a transformation such that the new dependent
 variable takes the conditional mean (given the original ordinal rating)
 of a standardised normally-distributed continuous variable, calculated
 based on the frequencies of the ordinal ratings in the sample (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "cornelisen:2006"

\end_inset

, provides a worked example).
 Where the assumption of normality in the continuous variable holds ---
 and in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "praag:2004a"

\end_inset

's examples, the results suggest it does --- probit-adapted OLS is equivalent
 to the ordered probit.
 Its advantage is that it is quicker to compute and can be used as a building
 block in more complex models.
 It does not appear to have been very widely used, although its results
 are reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stevenson:2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Limited SWB comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Abandoning or weakening the assumption of ordinal comparability is possible
 using techniques only relatively recently applied to SWB (there appears
 to be significant potential for the wider application of all of the following
 methods).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2004"

\end_inset

 develop and apply an ordered logit model with fixed individual effects
 and individual-specific thresholds.
 They find that inclusion of time-invariant individual effects qualitatively
 changes the results of their model; this contradicts the finding of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 12"
key "clark:2002"

\end_inset

, whose cardinal models suggest that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cross-section and panel equations seem to have similar general structures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "clark:2005a"

\end_inset

 assume that different groups or types of individuals have different happiness
 and/or reporting functions (which cannot be separated using their data),
 and hence estimate an ordered latent class model in which the classes vary
 both in the marginal contribution of income to SWB and in the cut-points
 used to translate a latent continuous variable into observed SWB ratings.
 Their data identify 4 or 5 classes with significantly different reported
 happiness functions, suggesting that inter-individual heterogeneity is
 more complicated than can be fully modelled by simple fixed effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferrer-i-carbonell:2005"

\end_inset

 estimates SWB effects of an individual's own and reference group income
 using an ordered probit model with individual random effects (allowing
 for correlation between the random effects and a subset of explanatory
 variables using the Mundlak correction).
 The results are consistent with findings from cross-sectional methods:
 own income has a small but significant effect on SWB.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Anchoring vignettes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data sets in which anchoring vignette items are included alongside an SWB
 self-assessment permit two further approaches to correcting for differing
 reporting functions (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

) across individuals, given two key assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "king:2003"

\end_inset

.
 The assumptions are: vignette equivalence, which means different respondents
 need to understand the vignettes in the same way; and response consistency,
 which means that respondents need to use the response scale for the vignettes
 and for their self-assessment in the same way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A non-parametric transformation of the original ordinal SWB response into
 a new (potentially vector-valued) ordinal variable can be made 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "lau:2007"

\end_inset

.
 This can then be analysed with a variant of the standard ordered logit
 or probit which allows vector-valued ordinal responses.
 Alternatively, a parametric technique --- compound hierarchical ordered
 probit (chopit) --- can be used.
 This predicts individuals' cut-points on a latent continuous variable based
 on both their vignette responses and the values of independent variables,
 and does not require that every respondent answer the vignette items 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rabe-hesketh:2002,king:2003"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the chopit model with the Survey of Health, Ageing and Retirement
 in Europe (SHARE) data set --- the only known study incorporating vignettes
 for SWB --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "angelini:2008"

\end_inset

 find that higher life satisfaction ratings among Danish as compared to
 Italian retirees may be largely explained by differing interpretations
 of the response scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Explanatory variable treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the nature and appropriate treatment of the SWB data has been debated
 at length, comparatively little attention has been given to the treatment
 of explanatory factors in SWB research.
 Explanatory variables are generally entered into models in a linear specificati
on, save for income (usually logged) and age (usually in linear and quadratic
 forms).
 Most researchers have also assumed the effects of different explanatory
 variables to be independent, and potential interactions have not been widely
 explored (for example, could the SWB effect of having --- or not having
 --- children be partly contingent on age and gender?).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "yang:2008"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "yang:2008,yang:2008a"

\end_inset

 looks at interactions with life-course variables such as age and would
 represent an exception here, but writes outside of economics.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although several analyses incorporate spatially-derived data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "luechinger:2009,mackerron:2008,brereton:2007"

\end_inset

, only two so far seem to have attempted the econometric modelling of any
 spatial effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rehdanz:2007a,stanca:2010"

\end_inset

.
 Relevant spatial models could include: spatial explanatory variables models
 (in which a person's SWB is correlated with other observed characteristics
 of nearby individuals); spatial error models (in which SWB is correlated
 with unobserved characteristics of nearby individuals); spatial lag models
 (in which SWB is correlated with the SWB of nearby individuals); and models
 accounting for spatial heterogeneity in the relationships between variables.
 The lack of use of spatial models in economic SWB research to date may
 be at least partly explained by the relative scarcity of data that are
 spatially referenced at an appropriately high resolution.
 Spatial models could also be applied to relations in conceptual spaces,
 such as social networks (where by 'nearby', one means 'well known' or 'strongly
 related'), as they have begun to be in the medical literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fowler:2008,christakis:2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the degree of inter-correlation between many of the more important
 factors influencing SWB (such as age, income and employment) might suggest
 the use of techniques such as structural equation modelling (SEM) or principal
 components analysis (PCA), but these have not been widely used (although
 for SEM using domain satisfactions data, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:2003"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Causality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Establishing causality, especially with cross-sectional data, is a particularly
 difficult problem in happiness research.
 Happiness and wellbeing are such all-encompassing ideas that it is often
 difficult to be sure that happiness is not a cause of another variable
 (rather than, or as well as, being caused by it); or that an unobserved
 variable is not a cause of happiness (leading to omitted variables bias);
 or even that an 
\emph on
observed
\emph default
 variable does not cause happiness (for the purposes of an instrumental
 variables treatment, for example).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies using aggregated data --- usually mean SWB ratings at a whole-country
 level alongside other aggregated statistics such as GDP, or mean air pollution
 levels --- are potentially subject to the 'ecological fallacy' (the spurious
 inference of individual-level characteristics from group-level characteristics)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "robinson:2009"

\end_inset

, and face particular difficulties in establishing causality.
 And individual-level data sets, which have usually not been collected specifica
lly for the study of SWB, generally omit some things which might reasonably
 be expected to have a significant impact --- such as personality indicators,
 childhood experiences, traumatic events, or being in a relationship (even
 if unmarried) --- and which might not be independent of the variables that
 are the focus of the investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fixed effects treatments with panel data can of course help with some of
 these factors --- for example, genetic elements of SWB are fixed by definition,
 and other personality traits can be reasonably assumed to be broadly stable
 --- but even with panel data, omitted time-variant variables may be a problem.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

income movements and wellbeing movements may merely be linked because of
 omitted variables (such as seniority in the workplace)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 50"
key "gardner:2007a"

\end_inset

.
 As usual, the most robust evidence of causality is provided by natural
 experiments, in the form of exogenous shocks such as lottery wins (
\emph on
ibid.
\emph default
) or political shifts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "frijters:2004"

\end_inset

.
 Also as usual, natural experiments are not easy to identify, although the
 conclusions of the two studies cited, which focus on income, are encouragingly
 consistent with the broad consensus in the literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Valuation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:happiness-valuation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If SWB can be regarded as a proxy for PS-style utility, SWB model estimates
 can be used for monetary valuation.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 1373"
key "blanchflower:2004"

\end_inset

 use models estimated on US General Social Survey data to calculate dollar
 values for life events like unemployment and divorce, finding that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a lasting marriage (compared to widowhood as a ‘natural’ experiment)...
 is estimated to be worth $100,000 a year
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 provide an extended discussion of the SWB valuation method, on which the
 following account is based.
 The usual SWB regression specification in the literature is a simple additive
 model in which income is logged.
 For example, for reported SWB 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, income 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, and a good 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\alpha+\beta\ln(y)+\gamma g
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this, the implicit price of the good 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 --- which is the marginal rate of substitution between the good and income
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 --- is obtained at the mean wage 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\delta r/\delta q}{\delta r/\delta y}=\gamma\frac{\bar{y}}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The welfare effect of a discrete change in the amenity can also be measured
 in terms of the compensating surplus or equivalent surplus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Compensating surplus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compensating surplus 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the sum of money that would keep an individual at his or her original
 level of utility after a change in the provision of the good.
 It is calculated following a standard SWB regression estimation as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before the change, reported SWB 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 is modelled as a function of income 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and the good 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{0}=\alpha+\beta\ln(y)+\gamma g_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following a change in the provision of the good to 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

, reported SWB 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 becomes: 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\lang english

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{1}=\alpha+\beta\ln(y)+\gamma g_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compensating surplus 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is thus defined so as to satisfy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{0}=\alpha+\beta\ln(y-c)+\gamma g_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 produces:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\ln(y)+\gamma g_{0}=\beta\ln(y-c)+\gamma g_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which rearranges to give, at mean income 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\bar{y}-\exp\left(\ln(\bar{y})+\frac{\gamma}{\beta}(g_{0}-g_{1})\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equivalent surplus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalent surplus 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the amount of money that, if a particular change in the provision of
 the good were 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 to occur, would bring an individual the utility level they would have attained
 if that change had in fact taken place.
 It is calculated similarly, by setting:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{1}=\alpha+\beta\ln(y+e)+\gamma g_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To give, at mean income 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=-\bar{y}+\exp\left(\ln(\bar{y})+\frac{\gamma}{\beta}(g_{1}-g_{0})\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compensating surplus represents maximum willingness to pay (WTP) for
 an improvement in the good, or minimum willingness to accept (WTA) for
 a deterioration.
 Conversely, the equivalent surplus represents maximum WTP to avoid a deteriorat
ion in the good, or minimum WTA to forego an improvement 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "brookshire:1980"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Regression specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether these quantities represent the full value of the good is dependent
 on the specification of the SWB regression.
 For the full value to be derived, the SWB regression must include any other
 factors that compensate for variation in the good.
 Valuation using SWB has been applied primarily to spatial amenities such
 as environmental quality characteristics.
 In that context, in order to obtain total values, the regression specification
 must include house prices and wages.
 If house prices and wages are not included, then only residual values that
 are not capitalised in the housing and labour markets will be recovered
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If the markets are in equilibrium, these residual values are expected to
 be zero.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "luechinger:2009,ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Strengths and weaknesses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
before "e.g."
key "frey:2008a"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "welsch:2009"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fujiwara:2011"

\end_inset

 all provide summaries of the strengths and weaknesses of the SWB valuation
 method as compared with the standard alternatives --- revealed and stated
 preference techniques.
 In general, SWB valuation is presented as a complement rather than an alternati
ve to conventional valuation techniques, on the basis that it has quite
 different strengths and weaknesses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both revealed and stated preference methods ultimately rely on the PS foundation
s outlined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:ps-and-swb"

\end_inset

, which require that individuals are able to accurately predict the utility
 implications of (actual or hypothetical) choices.
 Research in behavioural economics (and psychology) lays these foundations
 open to considerable doubt 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "kahneman:2005,gilbert:2006"

\end_inset

, leading 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p.39"
key "fujiwara:2011"

\end_inset

 to argue that the main appeal of the SWB valuation is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

that it does not rely on people having well-defined pre-existing rational
 preferences
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Revealed and stated preference methods are subject to further limitations.
 Stated preference responses may be subject to framing effects, anchoring,
 scope insensitivity, neglect of substitutes or the budget constraint, strategic
 behaviour, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

warm glow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect of supporting a good cause, and protests (against the valuation
 exercise, the proposed payment mechanism, and so on).
 Stated preference studies may also be very costly to run.
 Hedonic pricing --- a common revealed preference method --- relies on the
 assumption that labour and housing markets are in equilibrium, and hence
 that these markets are unrestricted; that there is a wide variety of houses
 and jobs; that individuals know the relevant characteristics of all locations;
 that prices adjust immediately; and that transacting and moving are costless.
 These assumptions are unlikely to be fully met.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Valuation with SWB data does not suffer from these specific weaknesses.
 On the other hand, the method requires strong assumptions of its own.
 Crucially, as noted above, we must accept some particular SWB indicator
 as a proxy for PS-style underlying utility.
 As noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Concepts-and-terminology"

\end_inset

, a variety of concepts and indicators of SWB exist.
 In the context of valuation studies, 'life satisfaction' measures have
 been the most frequently used, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 15"
key "fujiwara:2011"

\end_inset

 argue that these have implicitly been assumed to most closely resemble
 the conventional PS notion of utility.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "powdthavee:2011"

\end_inset

 find that values calculated for health conditions can vary substantially
 --- in some cases, by orders of magnitude --- depending on the indicator
 used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SWB valuation imposes some further requirements.
 Practically, we must be assured of the quality of the SWB indicator and
 of the survey data of which it is a part, bearing in mind the issues discussed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:measuring-happiness"

\end_inset

.
 We must be persuaded that the SWB regression model takes the correct functional
 form, and that the relationships between the explanatory variables and
 SWB are causal --- points which are rarely dealt with in the literature.
 And we must be wary of assortment by tastes: for example, when valuing
 air pollution, it may be that less pollution-sensitive individuals live
 in more polluted locations (and vice versa), leading to underestimation
 of the SWB impact 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 493"
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike stated preference methods, SWB data cannot be used to value parameters
 outside of their observed (past and current) range.
 Although SWB valuation may be able to capture certain non-use values, such
 as for regional biodiversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rehdanz:2007a,ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

, it will not necessarily do so, since the simple existence of a good may
 not vary between surveyed individuals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 30"
key "fujiwara:2011"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As seen above, the effect of income on wellbeing is a key parameter in SWB
 valuation calculations.
 To date, most studies using the SWB valuation method have reported values
 that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

seem too large
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

, and researchers have generally supposed the cause of this to be an underestima
tion of this income effect.
 This underestimation, in turn, may have a range of causes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the coefficient on income may be biased downwards by measurement
 error, caused by wide response brackets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "frey:2004"

\end_inset

 or missing, misleading or mistaken responses on income-related survey questions
, or potentially by a failure to correct for household size
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "moro:2008"

\end_inset

 specify the SWB regression to include household income (logged) and dummies
 for number of children, but do not include household size or use a correspondin
gly equivalised income measure.
 Unusually, they also do not find a positive effect of marriage or cohabitation
 --- perhaps because these dummy variables also serve as indicators of lower
 income per household member.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, the omission of one's own lagged income or of the incomes of others
 may give rise to the same effect.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "welsch:2009a"

\end_inset

 notes, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

since, due to adaptation, lagged income affects life satisfaction negatively
 [...], and current income is positively correlated with lagged income, omission
 of lagged income may imply a downward bias in the estimate of the marginal
 utility of (current) income
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that one's income is also positively correlated with the other
 incomes against which one compares it, a similar argument may be made in
 regard of the omission of appropriate comparator incomes
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, as will be noted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Past-and-relative-income"

\end_inset

, it is not necessarily clear which the appropriate comparator incomes are.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, the effect of income may be underestimated by the failure to account
 for costs of income generation, such as working hours, commuting, and stress.
 To address this issue, income may be instrumented, for example with income
 of other household members and industry/occupation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

 (then again, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

 notes, a predicted income measure of this sort is also a good candidate
 for a comparator income estimate).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fourth, there may be simultaneous causation, such that being happier leads
 to increased earnings as well as the reverse 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 113"
before "e.g."
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

.
 And finally, indirect impacts of income on SWB may be absorbed by other
 explanatory variables, such as health.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 8"
key "dolan:2011"

\end_inset

 find the literature 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remarkably silent on this matter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and suggest a means for countering it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Is happiness valid economics?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Is-happiness-valid"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite the growth of SWB research within economics, it is not currently
 a fully mainstream approach.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Please note that the 'mainstream' is not here equated directly with the
 neo-classical orthodoxy presented in caricature above, nor is it suggested
 that it is a single, static, or easily-defined quantity; like the core
 of any discipline, it is in constant flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "colander:2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It continues to attract varying degrees of scepticism from within the PS
 tradition --- perhaps unsurprisingly, given the historical roots of the
 two approaches.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "smith:2008"

\end_inset

 writes: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I am 'unhappy' with happiness economics...
 It is amazing to me that the best economics journals have devoted so much
 attention to what Dan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hamermesh:2004"

\end_inset

 has previously described as 'rather silly' analyses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Most criticism can be classified into three major levels, which are decreasingl
y fundamental: the epistemological, the practical, and the disciplinary.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, epistemologically, it is held that subjective experiences are ultimately
 unmeasurable and incommensurable: I can never prove that my experience
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yellow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the same as yours 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gilbert:2006"

\end_inset

, and the same goes for happiness concepts of all kinds.
 This, of course, is the very same observation that turned 19th century
 economists away from subjective accounts of wellbeing.
 In principle, it is inescapable; in practice, for much of the time, it
 seems to matter very little.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Although it may seem somewhat unsatisfactory, there are strong precedents
 for disregarding basic philosophical challenges to a dominant world view:
 free will, for example, is essentially philosophically impossible given
 any meaningful definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "strawson:2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many sources of evidence that SWB reports are meaningful, and
 that different people mean similar things by them.
 Current happiness or satisfaction is a strong predictor of future behaviour
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 136"
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

.
 It correlates strongly with objective indicators including neural activity
 (measured with MRI), heart rate, blood pressure, smiling and suicide, and
 subjective data including recall of positive and negative events and others'
 SWB assessments --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "pp. 370--371"
key "tella:2005"

\end_inset

 summarise these connections concisely.
 State-by-state variation in US SWB levels is also substantially correlated
 with compensating differentials calculated using objective quality-of-life
 data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "oswald:2010,gabriel:2003"

\end_inset

.
 Especially given our evolutionary/genetic similarity, none of this should
 seem terribly surprising 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "veenhoven:2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, practically, it is argued that even if it is possible to use SWB
 data, various measurement issues will bias the results, particularly where
 a subjective measure is used as a dependent variable.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bertrand:2001"

\end_inset

 offer a clear statement of this position; they are especially pessimistic,
 in terms of the notation introduced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:ps-and-swb"

\end_inset

, regarding the independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The availability of longitudinal or panel data offers some reassurance
 in relation to such criticism, however, since individual fixed effects
 can be used to control for the time-invariant elements of any such relationship
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "frey:2002a"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
** counter-argument here? **
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And third, in disciplinary terms, it is suggested that while SWB analyses
 represent a valid and even interesting line of inquiry, it is not one to
 be pursued within economics.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hamermesh:2004"

\end_inset

 elaborates: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we should not abandon our comparative advantage --- our frameworks for analysing
 maximising behaviour by individuals and how that behaviour affects individual
 and group outcomes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, happiness economics has drawn interest from those expressly
 calling for a broadening of disciplinary scope: pluralist, heterodox and
 'post-autistic' movements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "guerrien:2004,fullbrook:2005,george:2007,kaskarelis:2007"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hamermesh (possibly alongside some of the more radical post-autists) arguably
 presents a false choice here.
 Accepting SWB research as a useful endeavour need not imply abandoning
 other analytical frameworks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 3"
key "diener:2009"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, one of the strongest arguments in favour of the application of
 SWB methods is that their strengths 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 weaknesses are quite different from --- and even complementary to --- the
 strengths and weaknesses of methods recently favoured in the mainstream
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "welsch:2009,ott:2008"

\end_inset

.
 For example, non-market valuation methods based on SWB scores require a
 quite different set of assumptions and simplifications than more established
 revealed- and stated-preference methods.
 They can therefore offer corroboration (or otherwise) of those other methods'
 results, or be applied where those methods' assumptions are plainly inapplicabl
e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ultimately, the status of SWB research is a matter of shifting social consensus
 within the discipline; any attempt to put the issue on firmer ground appears
 likely to turn out rather circular (a problem that is concisely encapsulated
 in the popular definition of economics as 'what economists do' --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
after "2"
key "backhouse:1997"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
*** also -- plenty of the criticisms made of happiness research turn out
 to apply only to a specific method, or a specific data set, or a specific
 application of a method to a data set; while certain critics seem to urge
 dismissal/abandonment of the entire subject of inquiry based on these limited
 criticisms? ***
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Who are the happiness economists?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Who"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are not, or at least were not until recently, any dedicated 'happiness
 economists'.
 Happiness economics has been done by people in various areas --- and on
 various edges --- of the discipline.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In addition, of course, to being influenced by and indebted to those working
 in other disciplines, most notably psychology (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "cantril:1965"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One may therefore ask which areas of economics, and which economists, have
 been most closely associated with which aspects.
 Three major areas are outlined below --- as well as one area more notable
 by its absence from this field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Macroeconomics: growth, national accounting, unemployment and taxation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Macroeconomics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted above, Easterlin's 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "easterlin:1974"

\end_inset

 paper, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Does economic growth improve the human lot?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, is often cited as an early (re)introduction of SWB into economics.
 Connections between income and happiness at the national and international
 scales have since been a important strand of happiness research (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "oswald:1997"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "hagerty:2003"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "blanchflower:2004"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "brockmann:"

\end_inset

), and one which has obviously close ties with work looking at income and
 happiness on the individual level (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "easterlin:2001"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "boes:2006a"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "layard:2008a"

\end_inset

).
 The precise nature of these connections remains a matter of some contention,
 though (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "stevenson:2008"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The macro-level research has naturally also led to consideration of SWB
 as one of the alternatives --- or complements --- to GDP as an index of
 national or social 'progress' (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "diener:2004"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kahneman:2004"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "tella:2008"

\end_inset

).
 In this form --- perhaps most famously championed by the Bhutanese government,
 with its measures of Gross National Happiness (GNH) --- it has been of
 substantial interest to other governments and politicians (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:public-policy"

\end_inset

).
 SWB measures also feature within composite indicators such as the New Economics
 Foundation's 'Happy Planet Index' (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "nef:2006"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "nef:2007"

\end_inset

).
 Of course, any aggregated indicator of social well-being raises challenging
 questions in relation to social welfare functions and utilitarian ethics
 (again, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:public-policy"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Still at the macro level, the aggregate impacts of (un)employment, inflation
 and tax policy have been studied in some depth (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Clark:1994"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "layard:2005a"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "blanchflower:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "clark:2008"

\end_inset

).
 Rivalry, habituation, and other psychological and sociological factors
 are involved in these effects, giving this work strong connections with
 behavioural economics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Behavioural economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Behavioural economics investigates how real economic actors actually behave
 (make decisions), and seeks to provide explanations --- primarily psychological
 and sociological ones --- as to why they behave as they do 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "rabin:2002"

\end_inset

.
 Neo-classical utility theory provides a baseline for comparison with empirical
 data: behavioural predictions based on rational individual (decision) utility
 maximisation.
 Behaviour may deviate from these predictions for reasons such as loss aversion,
 anchoring effects, and myopia (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "hsee:2006"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kahneman:2006b"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "offer:2006"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "camerer:2005"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Understanding these deviations can help us to form better predictions about
 future behaviour, and potentially to devise means by which people's choices
 could be 'improved' (such as by the use of well-chosen 'sticky' default
 options or 'nudges' --- such as automatically enrolling employees in match-fund
ed pension schemes --- as envisaged in the 'libertarian paternalism' of
 Thaler & Sunstein (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "thaler:2003"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyear
key "thaler:2008"

\end_inset

)).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Happiness economics provides an alternative baseline, allowing researchers
 to assess how far behaviour deviates from that which would appear to have
 maximised experienced utility or SWB.
 By recognising a distinction between decision and experienced utility,
 it permits analysis of a further reason for apparently sub-optimal behaviour:
 imperfections in individuals' ability to predict their own future experienced
 utility or SWB under different scenarios.
 Established examples of such imperfections include over-estimation of the
 extent to which one's future tastes will resemble one's current tastes
 ('projection bias' --- 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "loewenstein:2003"

\end_inset

), and failure to anticipate the extent of habituation to rises in one's
 income 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "layard:2005a"

\end_inset

.
 (The former may lead to over-consumption of durable goods, and the latter
 to excess pursuit of income and consumption in general, relative to the
 apparent SWB optima).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experienced utility or SWB measures also enable behavioural economics to
 address questions beyond the scope of analyses limited to data on preferences
 revealed through choices, including examining the contexts of choice and
 the effects on (experienced) utility of choices made within different choice
 
\emph on
sets
\emph default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "koszegi:2008"

\end_inset

.
 Such work can indicate, for example, that more choice is not always preferable
 in SWB terms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "schwartz:2002"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environmental and ecological economics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Environmental-and-ecological"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One interesting application of SWB data has been to non-market valuation.
 Estimated relationships between levels of an arbitrary good and SWB, and
 between SWB and income, can together be used to derive the good's marginal
 value.
 A particular strength of SWB-based valuation is its applicability to questions
 where little individual choice is involved, such as mental health or community
 life 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "layard:2010"

\end_inset

.
 Valuation using SWB has so far attracted the attention of environmental
 economists in particular.
 The use of SWB for environmental valuation is thoroughly reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "welsch:2009"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ferreira:2010"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within 
\emph on
ecological
\emph default
 economics --- which has, like happiness economics, been somewhat isolated
 from the economic mainstream to date 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dasgupta:2008"

\end_inset

 --- SWB is of interest in part because it makes strong sustainability more
 palatable.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Strong sustainability proposes limits to the substitutability of natural
 capital with other forms, and this implies that the scale of resource extractio
n and of the production of wastes requiring assimilation, relative to the
 biosphere, is of some importance (the rather unfashionably expressed propositio
n of 'limits to growth' (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "meadows:1972"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "meadows:2004"

\end_inset

).
 It is increasingly widely accepted that the scale of certain activities
 --- including in particular the emission of greenhouse gases --- is already
 close to or beyond sustainable limits (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "millennium-ecosystem-assessment:2005"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "treasury:2006"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "ipcc:2007"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Strong sustainability appears to require future economic growth to rely
 less on material goods, and/or to proceed at a slower (or even negative)
 rate (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "victor:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "nef:2006a"

\end_inset

).
 Under the neo-classical PS model, growth in individual and national income
 is effectively synonymous with growth in individual utility and social
 welfare.
 The PS approach therefore appears to predict a rather dismal future under
 any feasible regime: reduced utility deriving from unintended ecological
 overshoot on the one hand; intentionally reduced growth, and therefore
 utility, on the other.
 But since, at least in theory, growth in SWB could be de-coupled from GDP
 growth, SWB might offer a theoretical route out of this dismal future (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "welsch:2009a"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "jackson:2005"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "gowdy:2005"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "dolan:2006b"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Marks:2006"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
*** climate change => additional term for Kaya identity? ***
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To imagine such a way out requires an emphasis on non-income factors that
 utility theory typically assumes to be held constant, and which happiness
 research tends to find are strongly related to SWB, including family life,
 social ties and environmental quality.
 Ecological economists --- as well as civil society groups, and policy-makers
 and their advisers --- have therefore become increasingly interested in
 the relation of happiness to these factors.
 And ecological and environmental economists are understandably particularly
 interested in happiness in relation to environmental quality parameters
 and their valuation (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:2005"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "welsch:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "rehdanz:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "mackerron:2008"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "luechinger:2009"

\end_inset

), to environmental attitudes and behaviours 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "brown:2005,ferrer-i-carbonell:2007"

\end_inset

, and to the potential disconnection between consumption and well-being
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "csikszentmihalyi:2000,sanne:2002,layard:2005,scitovsky:1977"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The more radical end of the SWB and consumption literature, drawing on work
 from psychology, suggests that the economic and social system in developed
 economies is partly predicated on a level of structural or manufactured
 dissatisfaction, in more-or-less direct opposition to SWB.
 Such dissatisfaction, in which advertising plays an important role, helps
 to ensure that people remain motivated to consume (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "kasser:2002,jackson:2004,kasser:2007"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

