\begin_layout Subsection
Others
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:who-Others"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, happiness work has not been exclusive to these areas.
 For example, the work of the 'Leyden school', led by Bernard van Praag
 and Arie Kapteyn at Leyden university from the early 1970s (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:1968"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:1971"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:1973"

\end_inset

), is sometimes taken to represent a precursor of or complement to more
 recent work on SWB 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "praag:2006"

\end_inset

.
 Although the Leyden school's primary focus has been on financial satisfaction,
 it has also investigated broader life satisfaction measures --- as commonly
 employed in SWB research --- and more general methodological issues around
 subjective response data (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "soest:2007"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "praag:2004a"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Development (or who 
\emph on
aren't 
\emph default
the happiness economists?)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Development"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One area of the discipline which has 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 been a significant incubator for happiness research, despite a shared scepticis
m regarding the sufficiency of income- or consumption-based welfare indicators,
 is development economics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent development research has been increasingly influenced by the capability
 approach described by Sen and others.
 Capability relates to a person's positive freedom --- envisaged as the
 range and quality of opportunities (or 'functionings') that a person both
 has reason to value and is able attain --- and as such represents 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

an unusual intermediary between objective wellbeing and subjective wellbeing
 concepts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 351"
key "gasper:2007"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of habituation or adaptation to bad circumstances (whether through
 simple conditioning or broader cultural or religious indoctrination) has
 largely been seen as precluding the use of SWB in development work: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inequalities and exploitations survive in the world through making allies
 out of the deprived and exploited.
 The underdog learns to bear the burden...
 Discontent is replaced by acceptance...
 the horrors look less terrible in the metric of utilities
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 309"
key "sen:1984"

\end_inset

.
 However, it is possible that this position both overstates the problem
 of adaptation in relation to SWB and understates it in respect of capabilities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "clark:2009a"

\end_inset

.
 Some have even suggested that SWB could encompass rather than compete with
 capability in the evaluation of poverty 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kingdon:2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of the wellbeing ideas discussed in this paper, capability probably shares
 most with the objective lists account 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see"
key "dolan:2007a"

\end_inset

, and the relationship between capability and more subjective wellbeing
 accounts is not straightforward.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 162"
key "comim:2005"

\end_inset

 sees a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

remarkable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 lack of mutual acknowledgement between the two literatures, and describes
 some key contrasts: while capability draws principally from moral and political
 philosophy, SWB has a primarily neurological/psychological/sociological
 base; capability assessments privilege qualitative aspects, whereas SWB's
 empirical approach is almost exclusively quantitative; and where capability
 admits of normative 'anchors' for assessing wellbeing --- anchors such
 as autonomy and fairness --- SWB has no obvious normative content beyond
 standard utilitarianism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What does happiness economics tell us?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:findings"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, the literature gives a fairly consistent picture of which factors
 have what associations with SWB.
 Where studies' findings do contrast, an important cause may be endogeneity,
 in that one (or both) of the studies fails to control for correlated explanator
y factors.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, the effects of gender and care-giving, of religion and sociable
 group attendance, of age and wealth, or equivalised household income and
 family size, could each be correlated; hence a study that did not control
 for wealth might well report a different relationship between age and SWB
 than one that did.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since several authors have reviewed the specific findings of the SWB literature
 in detail 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "frey:2002,dolan:2008"

\end_inset

, this paper touches on the topic only briefly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Income and wealth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The impact of income measures on SWB has, as stated above, been a major
 focus of the SWB literature.
 This may be due in part to the centrality of the income/SWB relationship
 when using SWB data for monetary valuation.
 Researchers have investigated absolute income, income relative to others',
 and income relative to past income.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

 provide a detailed survey.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Absolute income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, absolute income is found to have a significant and positive
 association with individuals' SWB, but one whose magnitude is dwarfed by
 the effects of other factors (such as health, labour market status and
 marital status), at least in developed countries.
 There is perhaps surprisingly little discussion in the literature regarding
 the appropriate measure(s) of absolute income: this could be individual
 income, household income, or equivalised household income (adjusted for
 household size and composition).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the assumption of decreasing marginal utility of income, most studies
 use a log income measure as the explanatory variable; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "layard:2008a"

\end_inset

 assume that the relationship is log-like (in that that the elasticity of
 marginal utility with respect to income is constant), but find that the
 marginal utility of income in fact declines somewhat 
\emph on
faster
\emph default
 than in proportion to the rise in income.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
They assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\begin{cases}
\dfrac{y^{1-\rho}-1}{1-\rho} & \rho\neq1\\
\log y & \rho=1
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is utility and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 income, and estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1.26$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Studies making use of exogenous income variation have helped to establish
 that the apparent impact of income on SWB is at least partly causal 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "gardner:2007a"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relatively small effect of absolute income measures on happiness has
 been one of the more interesting findings in the literature and --- given
 the emphasis placed on income in the standard economic account of wellbeing
 as preference satisfaction --- one that has seemed to demand explanation.
 One line of reasoning is that consumption is ultimately the quantity of
 interest under the preference satisfaction approach, and that reported
 income is a noisy and biased proxy, excluding goods provided by the State
 and deferred consumption via savings 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 111"
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

.
 Based on Australian survey data including items on net worth, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "S24"
key "headey:2004"

\end_inset

 conclude that wealth 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is at least as important to well-being and ill-being as income
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

.
 An additional and more widely studied explanation is that the emphasis
 on absolute income within the preference satisfaction account neglects
 the more important contribution of relative income measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Past and relative income
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Past-and-relative-income"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals' own past incomes are negatively associated with their current
 SWB.
 This habituation or adaptation effect is very substantial --- several studies
 find that adaptation eliminates more than half of the positive effect of
 income gains over the long term 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 111"
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

 --- and is not fully anticipated by individuals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "layard:2005a"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The income of an individual's reference group has also been widely found
 to have a significantly negative effect on his or her SWB; in fact, reference
 group income may be substantially more important than own absolute income
 for individual happiness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "knight:2009"

\end_inset

.
 It is generally assumed that this effect is caused by status concerns,
 sometimes described as rivalry or jealousy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Social comparisons could also work in the opposite direction if the rising
 income of others were interpreted as a signal of one's own future income
 possibilities.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "senik:2008a"

\end_inset

 identifies such an effect (described as the effect of information or ambition)
 in transitional eastern European economies and the US.
 Jealousy and ambition effects are not mutually exclusive.
 Their relative importance may depend on perceived income mobility and uncertain
ty --- higher levels of either implying a stronger ambition effect (
\emph on
ibid.
\emph default
) --- and on which of an individual's many potential reference groups is
 under consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most studies have defined the reference group as people who are similar
 on a specific set of characteristics (e.g.
 age, education, employment sector), using either cell averages (e.g.
 average income for individuals in the same age 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 education 
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

 employment sector category) or predicted incomes from a wage regression
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "clark:2008a"

\end_inset

.
 But reference groups can also be defined over a specific geographical area
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "luttmer:2005,knight:2009"

\end_inset

; as family members, friends, or work colleagues; or as explicitly reported
 by the SWB survey respondent (these approaches require more data, and have
 been less widely employed).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Income habituation and (if individuals make social comparisons primarily
 within their own countries) rivalry both help to explain the Easterlin
 Paradox --- that, although individuals' incomes in cross-sectional studies
 are positively related to their SWB, for many countries there appears to
 be no corresponding effect of rising GDP on average national happiness
 figures over time.
 They also suggest that economic growth is of rather less importance than
 economists have traditionally assumed (but this is a contested issue ---
 e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "stevenson:2008a"

\end_inset

).
 Rivalry implies that visible consumption imposes a negative externality
 on others, while unanticipated habituation to income implies that people
 will choose to work more and take less leisure than would be rational for
 them.
 Both of these effects could inspire corrective taxation policies (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "layard:2005a"

\end_inset

; see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:public-policy"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other factors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Except where other citations are given, the comprehensive review by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dolan:2008"

\end_inset

 provides further detail on the factors identified here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Personal and demographic characteristics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Good psychological and physical health both have a strong, positive effect
 on SWB, in line with intuition.
 Almost all studies find a U-shaped relationship between age and SWB, with
 the young and old being happiest.
 Where a gender difference is detected, women usually report slightly higher
 happiness.
 In the US, whites have on average higher SWB than African Americans.
 The impact of education varies between studies: in some it has no significant
 effect, while in others highest SWB is variously associated with lower,
 higher, and intermediate levels of education.
 Marriage and stable partnerships are highly positive for SWB (though the
 potential for omitted variables bias is large here); separation, divorce
 and widowhood are highly negative.
 Parental divorce is found in some (but not all) studies to reduce children's
 SWB in adulthood.
 Evidence on the effect on parents of having children is rather mixed, depending
 on the SWB measure, country, number and age of children, and parental situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Work and time use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unemployment has one of the largest negative impacts on SWB, independent
 of and larger than the associated material loss, reducing reported happiness
 by 5--15% (where scale cardinality is assumed).
 Evidence regarding the effects of different types and hours of employment
 is scarce and somewhat mixed.
 Commuting to work is associated with lower SWB levels, all other things
 being equal.
 Informal care-giving has a negative effect on SWB.
 Community involvement and volunteering may have a positive effect, but
 this finding is somewhat variable (depending on what is controlled for,
 and whether fixed effects are included).
 There is evidence, albeit somewhat limited, that physical activity promotes
 SWB.
 Finally, socialising and regularly attending church are both associated
 with higher SWB, while TV viewing goes with lower SWB 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bruni:2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Attitudes and beliefs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trust in 'most people', in the people in one's neighbourhood, and in institution
s such as the police and government are all positive predictors of SWB (although
 great caution is required when regressing subjective variables on other
 subjective variables).
 Religious beliefs are generally associated with higher SWB too.
 Political views have not been widely studied, but may affect the impacts
 of other circumstances, including which party is in power 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "tella:2005"

\end_inset

.
 Satisfaction in specific life domains tends to correlate positively with
 global SWB, and may partly or entirely mediate the effect of objective
 circumstances.
 SWB is also related to major personality traits such as extraversion and
 conscientiousness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "weiss:2008"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Economic and political environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
High unemployment rates may reduce SWB, although research is limited (high
 local unemployment rates may also ameliorate the impact of an individual's
 own unemployment, however).
 Inflation may also have a negative influence on SWB, especially for those
 with right wing politics.
 Democracy, and particularly direct or participative democratic systems,
 may be positive for SWB.
 Evidence on income inequality is very mixed; its effect may depend partly
 on real or perceived mobility.
 There is little evidence concerning the effects of social insurance and
 the welfare state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Natural and immediate environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Living in an unsafe or deprived area is, unsurprisingly, detrimental to
 SWB.
 Living in public housing may be negative for SWB 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "brereton:2007"

\end_inset

, but other aspects of housing quality seem to be little studied.
 Living in large cities appears unfavourable, while rural living has a positive
 impact in SWB terms (at least once lower rural incomes are controlled for).
 The evidence of environmental quality effects is still very limited, although
 several studies find a negative impact of air pollution on SWB.
 Some studies also find a link between climate and SWB, such that more extreme
 climates are detrimental.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variation in SWB explained by all observed factors is well below 50%
 in all studies, which may partly owe to an important (and unobservable)
 genetic component: one study of identical twins raised apart suggests that
 up to half of the variation in SWB could be genetically based 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 240"
key "tellegen:1988"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As with all heritability measures, however, this figure is as much dependent
 on the range of variation in material circumstances in one society at one
 time as it is on any genetic mechanism.
 For example, if all of a society's children were raised in absolutely identical
 circumstances, then the heritability of all traits --- being the percentage
 of variation accounted for by genetic factors --- would necessarily be
 100%.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What does this mean for public policy?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:public-policy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Happiness research has been a subject of substantial interest in the political
 and policy spheres.
 Following a 2007 conference hosted by the European Commission, European
 Parliament, Club of Rome, OECD and WWF, the OECD's 
\emph on
Measuring the Progress of Societies
\emph default
 and the European Commission's 
\emph on
Beyond GDP
\emph default
 projects aim to foster the development of non-GDP indicators, including
 happiness (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "european-communities:2009"

\end_inset

; http://www.oecd.org/progress/; http://www.beyond-gdp.eu/).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The French and German governments have commissioned recent reports on this
 topic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stiglitz:2009,kroll:2009"

\end_inset

, with the French president subsequently instructing the national statistics
 agency to give greater weight to quality of life issues 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jolly:2009"

\end_inset

.
 In Canada a network of governmental and non-governmental organisations
 is collaborating on a Canadian Index of Wellbeing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "institute-of-wellbeing:2009"

\end_inset

.
 In the UK, happiness entered electoral politics in the speeches of, and
 Quality of Life policy commission set up by, the UK Conservative Party
 leader 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cameron:2006,watt:2007"

\end_inset

.
 Its implications have been examined by a Strategy Unit report 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "donovan:2002"

\end_inset

, by Defra's Whitehall Well-being Working Group 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "easton:2006"

\end_inset

, by a Government Office for Science 'Foresight' project 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foresight-mental-capital-and-wellbeing-project:2008"

\end_inset

 and in various other departments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sustainable-development.gov.uk:2007"

\end_inset

, and the government has just announced that official 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

general wellbeing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indicators will in future be produced by the Office for National Statistics
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stratton:2010"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Update with ONS report and Treasury Green Book update.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those championing SWB in policy have tended to argue as a first step for
 just this kind of systematic measurement: the creation of wellbeing indicators,
 standing alongside existing economic indicators, to assess performance
 at national and/or regional levels 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "michaelson:2009"

\end_inset

.
 Policy in an extremely wide range of areas has potential to affect individuals'
 SWB; not only areas with an obvious and direct connection, such as mental
 health services, but also taxation, (un)employment, environment, and many
 more.
 It could be argued, therefore, that SWB considerations should inform policy
 development in those areas; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "veenhoven:2004"

\end_inset

, for example, writes that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the greatest happiness principle deserves a more prominent place in policy
 making
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This 'new utilitarianism' is potentially subject to the same variety of
 critiques as the traditional brand, however.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a philosophical level, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nozick:1974"

\end_inset

 finds a utilitarian system vulnerable to the so-called 'utility monster',
 who derives greater utility from the sacrifice of others than those others
 lose --- such that total utility is increased by sacrificing everybody
 to the monster --- and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "parfit:1986"

\end_inset

 offers the 'repugnant conclusion' that a world of many people just barely
 surviving could have greater total utility than a world of fewer people
 with higher individual utilities.
 In practice, these objections are easily dismissed: the 'utility monster'
 does not exist, and both arguments rely on naïve interpretations of Bentham's
 'greatest good for the greatest number' as a simple sum (or alternatively,
 in Nozick's case, average) of individual utilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But this point does raise an important question --- what 
\emph on
should
\emph default
 be the social welfare function that aggregates individual utilities? ---
 to which there is no clear answer.
 International SWB research often uses mean self-ratings, but this assumes
 cardinality and implies total agnosticism as to the distribution of happiness.
 A 'U-index' is a further possibility (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:domains-and-timescales"

\end_inset

).
 So too is an (ordinal-only) Pareto-optimality principle; but this is no
 less problematic in relation to the allocation of wellbeing than it is
 in relation to other resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sen:1978"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Of the Pareto-optimality principle, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "22"
key "sen:1978"

\end_inset

 writes: "This may seem alright as far as it goes, but how far does it go?
 ...
 If preventing the burning of Rome would have made the emperor Nero feel
 worse off, then letting him burn Rome would have been Pareto optimal.
 In short, a society or an economy can be Pareto optimal and still be perfectly
 disgusting."
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another class of objections to any role for SWB in the policy process concerns
 ethics and rights: unconstrained maximisation of a happiness indicator
 (or indeed any other indicator) could take societies in ethically questionable
 directions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 14"
key "johns:2007"

\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "ng:1997"

\end_inset

's arguments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
after "pp. 1849--50"
key "ng:1997"

\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

widespread use
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

electrical, chemical and mechanical stimulation of...
 the pleasure centres in our brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 seems not so far removed from the widespread use in Huxley's 
\emph on
Brave New World
\emph default
 of the drug 'soma' to induce blissful contentment with caste-based roles
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "veenhoven:2004"

\end_inset

; whether this is vision is utopian or dystopian is open to debate.
 As another example, the risk that the rights of minorities could be violated
 under a utilitarian principle is raised --- and alleged to have been realised
 in the form of ethnic cleansing in the Kingdom of Bhutan 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 70"
key "johns:2007"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In essence, the criticism here is that utilitarianism is a purely consequentiali
st ethical theory, concerned only with the outcomes of actions, and therefore
 fails to place off-limits actions which are widely held to be wrong.
 But this criticism is of a straw man.
 In practice, there is no reason why the consideration of likely happiness
 outcomes in relation to policy should be accompanied by the jettisoning
 of all ethical rules, including deontological ideas about what is inherently
 right or wrong.
 Maximising happiness is no more sinister than maximising income or any
 other quantity; it is only that the most relevant rule-based constraints
 on our means of doing so may not be the same for every maximand.
\end_layout

